Inflation in Europe has been driven by a drop in food prices
The accelerated inflation rate in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, prices in the 13 euro area countries rose more than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent, the European Community Statistics Office in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts have only shown 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the key interest rate by saying that lower interest rates, together with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to a spiraling inflation.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to 2%.
One analyst said that this was the catch 22 for the ECB: "inflation must be discouraged" so that it would not have to be addressed later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record over the past 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to rapidly rising food and energy prices.
The future market shares of cereals increased by 88 per cent and the price of soybeans also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world's oil price has increased by 52 percent, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 in 2008 to 2.5% this year but will fall to 1.9 in 2009.
Analysts say the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, but the next three to four months the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut the key rate twice in 2008.
Gallup points to a government crisis
After a long stagnation, the Fidesz (Young Democratic Alliance) supporters increased significantly in early December, and it now has the largest number of supporters since 2002, compared to a previous low 13 percent of the Socialist support from Gallup (Survey Institute).
For loyal voters, the difference would be, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, support of more than two thirds (71%) against support of a fifth (20%) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the survey, the MDF (Hungarian Democratic Forum) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the parliamentary threshold: their support is two percent of the population.
Among the loyal voters who were certain to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious has never been higher, rising to 41% and 46% further say the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of the past spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects a worsening situation and only one tenth expects an improvement.
Last December, 71 percent of respondents - a majority that has never been seen in previous Gallup polls - felt that the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
Thirteen percent of the respondents trust or have a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent have no confidence in the Prime Minister and 27 percent in the Fidesz chairman.
One indicator of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society who think that discontent with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While after the October riots 35 percent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, the current rate is only 20 percent.
When asked about voting intentions, 60 percent of respondents said they would definitely vote and the other 20 percent said they would probably.
In comparison, for a "parliamentary election next Sunday", only 55% of the respondents would certainly participate and an additional 15% would probably.
74 percent of people would say no to higher education tuition fees, 79 percent would say no to counseling fees, and 84 percent would say no to hospital stays.
If we look only at the same proportions of people who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital accommodation fees, respectively.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent.
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs business triangle maintained the average price increase of 16% from last year, while this year the VAT rate did not increase.
The article by Napi Gazdaság (Economy of Everyday Life)
This year, in the Budaörs business triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also grew by an average of 16 percent, with a value increase of well over a thousand forints being seen in all supermarkets.
Prices, which had already skyrocketed in the grocery store in December, have not risen sharply from the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below 9,000 forints last year now cost more than 10,000 forints.
The daily shopping basket in the supermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological threshold of at least 91, 000 forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003 this was HUF 6,800.)
Prices of unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices of turkey, walnut and duck have risen sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Statistical Institute) but in Auchan, bread weighed only one kilogram at 139 forins.
Competition did not bring the price of the product below HUF 200.
It was surprising that, even in this supermarket, the price of the bottle of two liters of Coca-Cola was less than FIR 200 and therefore the bottle included only FIR 257.
But this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the least expensive.
According to our calculations, Cora raised the price of her daily basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan raised them by about 18 percent and 18 percent respectively.
Comparing the most expensive shopping cart last year with the cheapest shopping cart this year, we see a 12 percent gap whereas the difference between the cheapest and the most expensive shopping cart last year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1 480 forints.
Last year prices increased by an average of 1 206 forints, although the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticeable in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has made trade confusing, hypermarkets being unable to clearly determine what margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price changes on consumers.
(If a trader miscalculated the rotation of a product, he could lose a large profit on the margin adjusted to the intensity of the trade.)
As a result of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the prices of the daily basket has been so excessive that the most expensive basket was HUF 1 720 above the value of the 2006 basket, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was HUF 844 only.
This year the difference was not so great, as the value of the most expensive basket was HUF 1 630 higher than last year and the prices of the least expensive basket also increased HUF 1 284.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic rise in prices, with prices of everyday consumer goods rising by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets in less than 20 months.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some basic foods, the Statistical Institute has seen prices rise by more than 30% in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
According to the latter's daily basket, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, which was already very expensive last year, has risen by just over 10% compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get the brutal price increase to be accepted by multinational companies as well.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they are constantly recording good years.
In our experience, most customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets they visit.
They buy everything in bulk, they take the long-term food in palette.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed at the three supermarkets' boxes as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, we have heard that the turnover is less important in the province, and many multinationals complain to survey companies that they are not even reaching the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mostly caused by the misuse of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the lack of beds, and the overworking of medical staff do not help to prevent infections, says the chief physician of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save money on disinfectants
A few years ago, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected in a man hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
Earlier this year, a similar infection occurred at the same location.
The man who was seriously injured in a car accident was released from the hospital but soon afterwards had to return because of an MRSA infection and since then doctors have been unable to perform any major surgery on him because of the bacteria in his body.
As of 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Hospital Monitoring System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician at the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Which is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. by methicillin-oxacillin resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by AS (such as angina, amygdala, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used in an excessive or inappropriate manner, the bacteria, which respond well to antibiotics, will develop a resistant bacteria that will quickly proliferate in bad hospital conditions.
If the immune system temporarily or for a long time fails to function properly, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly, underweight or weakened patients.
According to the hospital's chief physician János, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of everyday life in hospitals.
The most important thing is not to confuse infection with epidemic, because MRSA is not only found in the area or not looked for, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The A.S. is resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the healthcare staff are wearing rubber gloves and protective masks, and we have antibiotics to treat them", said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients who are hospitalized are examined in advance for MRSA, but infection cannot always be prevented.
The sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of MRSA infections could be prevented but the current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection is mainly seen in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not the trend in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases only emerge if MRSA infection is detectable in the patient, said the chief medical officer of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts are needed to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, that is, microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient and basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs spread from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
The Commission has also adopted a number of measures to ensure that the health of the patients is not affected by the disease.
MRSAs spread through infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and contact, but due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, rooms are often full, beds are often too close to each other, while in the case of epidemics, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in financial difficulty, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the number of patients is high, so the risk of contamination is even higher, Karolina Böröcz said.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the spread of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why the fight against this infection is everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this programme is effective and MRSA infections are showing a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) identifies among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs as well) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, who was involved in a fatal accident, was not drunk.
The official statement on the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement has been drawn up.
It is possible that the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has since resigned from his post, who crushed a pedestrian causing his death last Tuesday, was driving drunk or dizzy, said Attila Morvai, spokesman for the capital's public ministry, on Friday after the findings were made.
The findings confirmed the first result of the investigation which already found that the former Commissioner had not drunk alcohol before he started driving.
Last Tuesday, the former chief of the 22nd District police station crushed a 55-year-old man who found himself facing him when he was driving his own car through Kossuth Lajos Street in the 22nd District.
(After all, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, as the Road Code states that a car that starts a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
The Commissioner resigned from his post following the accident and asked to retire because, according to the police report, the accident had left him very upset.
The investigation of this case is being carried out by the Budapest Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner had cooperated from the outset with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
The Commission will also be able to provide a detailed report on the implementation of the programme.
Hungary's Finance Minister János Veres and the European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice-President Marta Gajecka signed three agreements in Budapest on Friday for a credit line totalling EUR 400 million to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environmental projects to be implemented from the Cohesion Fund, a credit agreement of EUR 100 million having already been signed by the parties.
The EUR 150 million loan agreement also covers the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, the remaining EUR 150 million will be used later following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties signed a €50 million contract for innovation, which will be used primarily by the State budget for the research and development project at the University of Debrecen.
The project for line 4 of the subway was also discussed during the negotiations.
The parties agreed that they would renegotiate the possible amendment of the initial contract once Hungary has finalized the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for financing 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans at the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and no commitments.
Bulgaria, the EU real estate market paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, and the attention of all Europe has turned to this country in the Balkans, which has not been mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market which is still the cheapest but which will soon become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular destination in Eastern Europe for real estate with its ski apartments and cheap seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sables", the "Sunshine Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but there are increasing numbers looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik areas as well.
According to Re/Max Bulgaria analysts, sooner or later the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also attract investors and they are also increasingly buying in the cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, with commercial and office spaces promising the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of the most attractive golf destinations in Europe and thus a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the Bansko area.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time trying to change their lives, their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly Romania.
The Commission has also proposed that the Commission should take the necessary measures to ensure that the measures taken are not distorted.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to move in buy renovated buildings, which cost between 50 and 100 thousand euros, or old houses that are in disrepair, which cost between 5 and 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication, proximity to a large city, shops and in general the proximity of the local doctor.
The second group includes secondary home buyers (Bulgaria has been listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany since last December).
The third group is comprised of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium or long-term value added.
The price of buildings in the capital is rising constantly as a result of increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but they have increased by 21 percent each year over the past five years.
The increase in real estate prices is essentially greater than the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the press release from Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the professional meetings will end on Tuesday, however, on Wednesday, after the official opening, the ministers' negotiations on the post-2012 international climate regime will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is expected to define efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol's emission reduction period until 2012.
At present, there is a lively discussion on this subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that at the moment it did not wish to discuss exact figures, but was willing to sign an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent by 2020 from 1990 levels.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves, apart from reducing emissions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors likely within the framework of the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF), said Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister for Environment and Water, Gábor Fodor, confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its role as a flagship in global climate protection efforts and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU committed to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 20% from 1990 levels by 2020 irrespective of whether the Agreement was successfully signed after 2012, and was ready to reduce them to 30% if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also willing to make commitments appropriate to their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997 the Kyoto Protocol signatory countries had all set a target of reducing emissions by 5.2 per cent and that all 15 EU members at the time had committed to an 8% reduction.
Hungary has committed itself to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the 1985-87 period.
The challenge is high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the agreement's entry into force would certainly be postponed beyond 2012. In this case, commitments to reduce below the values set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was highlighted in the new IPCC report, the international scientific body that won the UN Nobel Peace Prize for its work on climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British Army is recruiting on YouTube
The British Army units report on the video sharing site recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in an attempt to make themselves popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that became passionate about YouTube: Special Operations Units in Afghanistan have been uploading video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reported.
These recordings, taken using miniature headset cameras, are monitored at the Air Force Headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London or uploaded to the Internet by the compatriots.
The political message is essential
The Air Force has already posted 139 footage on the network and their "chain" has been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The UK Ministry of Defence joined the group as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and it is releasing videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peace Keeping Force in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the Air Force's initial objective, the videos were posted online for recruitment and, according to the Ministry of Defense, were also used to inform the general public about the actual objectives of the military's presence abroad.
Propaganda published by this means costs virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, said defence consultant Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC.
The Americans played a game.
The army is upset because, apart from the videos that are carefully composed and censored, amateur videos have been posted on the sharing site that also show, for example, the deaths of soldiers: in the propaganda films official, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the battle.
In fact, many videos had already been posted on the Internet showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on real missions, but the British military has only recently been packing up for the upload of these videos.
The Americans recruit a little differently using the free-to-download America's Army shooter game, in which the player can directly take the place of the soldiers in a more or less real simulation.
