The forces of the mega strike are gathering
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will form their strike committee on Friday, which will coordinate the strike on Monday.
A general protest meeting will be held on Saturday and the strike will begin on Monday, the day of the final vote on the health funds bill.
This action will certainly cause significant traffic jams as rail traffic will be almost completely stopped and employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 1 p.m.
The union's unions will announce the details of their strike on Monday, organised with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The strike committee of LIGA-MOSZ will also be set up, and will be the coordinator of Monday's actions.
A general protest meeting will be held on Saturday and, starting Monday, the organisations joining the strike will suspend work indefinitely if they cannot reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in Parliament on the Health Insurance Act, is not set.
If the National Assembly does not pass the Health Insurance Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide what to do next.
The agenda of the National Assembly on Monday suggests that the vote on the health funds bill will likely take place late in the evening or even at night.
Due to the planned strike on Monday, traffic is expected to be heavily blocked: railways will stop working indefinitely and in the morning some public transport in Budapest and more than half of Volán companies may be stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half the road will be blocked as well.
Many unions and civil organisations joined the call for the strike, and the list is updated on the League's website.
Some organisations report an indefinite strike, others have declared a temporary stoppage.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Trade Union of Railways (VDSZSZ) had not been able to reach an agreement on minimum services, but as Christmas approaches, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current communications, public transport in Budapest will strike from the start of service until 1 p.m., Budapest airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the Electricity and Thermal Energy Industry Unions of the League will strike for four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Teachers' Union have called for two hours and two hours to eight hours respectively.
The National Association of Doctors will strike nationwide in alternating stages, and the SZEF-affiliated Health and Social Workers' Union (EDDSZ) will strike for two hours.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is that the government withdraw its proposal for health reform and submit a new design to social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating pensions to be introduced from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third claim is a guarantee of retirement before the legal age, which would allow the system to carry out the functions it deserves before 2010.
The fourth ground for action is the rejection by the Free Trade Union of Railways (VDSZSZ), affiliated to the League's trade unions, of the proposal from the Ministry of Economy and Transport on secondary railways and the waiting for another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased risk country
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, which was established in August last year with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary), increases the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
In its  Risk Warning , the company notes that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that  in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes may occur following the worsening of the already existing ethnic tension between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population of Hungary .
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors:  public actors have shifted the public debate on the Roma issue to representatives of radical and extreme political groups who have based their political strategy on the dispute between the Roma and the Hungarians 
The problem is getting worse, normal dialogue is becoming impossible, extremists are being strengthened and aggressive conflicts are more likely, they say.
According to the research institute, the Hungarian Guard's activity has significantly deteriorated Hungary's image abroad, particularly in terms of confidence in the country's stability and democratic maturity.
They recall that following increased publicity given to the reorganisation of Hungarian radical and far-right groups since autumn 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007 under the name of National Self-Defense Association.
 The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civil organization while publicly declaring the preparation of their members for defence missions (disaster, national defence, law enforcement), armed if necessary, and, moreover, citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state , they added.
They reported that everything was done according to a method which, based on the resentment of the political and party society, seeks to disguise different political ambitions as a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civil status and the status of associations thus serves not only to avoid the legal pitfalls of registering such associations in court but also to constitute a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a factor that increases the risk compared to neighbourly relations.
 In recent months, many neighbouring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk and the ultra-nationalist political actors of some neighbouring countries want to justify their anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the constitution of the Hungarian Guard.
This is affecting the political stability of the region, they added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not unique to Central and Eastern Europe, as political risks have increased throughout the region.
As they say, the functioning of the Hungarian Guard is similar, for example, to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose constitution was declared by the Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
The many Roma riots that broke out in a neighbourhood of Sofia (Kraszna Poljana) were the cause of the establishment of the Bulgarian Guard.
Taking advantage of these events, the UN decided to set up a guard, saying that the organisation's objective is  national self-defense .
They say that over the past 17 years, the Gypsies have terrorized Bulgaria but the state has remained inactive and neutral, recalls Political Capital.
They added that the initiative had sparked a lively debate in Bulgarian public opinion.
As they say, the statement by some organizations of Bulgarian Roma about the constitution of their own guard as a form of resistance signals an increased risk of ethnic clashes.
The functioning of the Hungarian Guard, which is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, does not exclude the possibility that Hungarian Roma respond to the threat in the same way by organising their own self-defense, as stated in the Risk Warning of Political Capital.
At the request for information from the telegraph agency, Attila Juhász, Director of Research at Political Capital, said: Risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
