Banks want to solve the crisis
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the central banks of England, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together the financial market crisis.
More than $100 billion will be put on the money markets through auctions.
The banks will be able to sell the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money by means of an auction system.
For example, the US Fed will auction out $40 billion and will also provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss Central Banks.
This is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the central banks of individual States have decided on such concerted action to prevent or even lessen the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to address the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend", writes Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group in his report to clients.
"The concerted action of the central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent", Baumohl adds in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion on unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect billions more to be lost.
"If the central banks have chosen this approach, they must really understand what may still follow", says ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad", he adds.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficulty accessing loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the US economy into a recession that could affect global economic growth.
The central banks made this choice after the London Interbank Rate, called LIBOR, which was used to borrow on the interbank market, failed to be lowered.
This meant that banks were still afraid of mutual borrowing, even though the central banks of the United States, Canada and England had lowered their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"This will have the same effect as a further decline in interest rates", says Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting.
