A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives at Bad Arolsen, which trace the fate of 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are now open to the public.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on a 27 km line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far available only for humanitarian purposes, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or his rightful owners.
The eleven governments - Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all the States has been completed, and the opening-up has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research  to be carried out, including on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced labour , says Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the public disclosure of these nominative documents because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deportation victims.
The records of concentration camps or arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo were collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the deported or forced labourers and, if necessary, to provide proof of their internment, in order to make way for compensation.
Even today, in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 full-time employees handle tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for some scientists, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
 There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents , said in 2006 Prof Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Centre for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin.
