Car insurance, which covers the driver in the event of an accident, involves a significant expense which will depend on various factors, such as age, gender, age of the driving licence, civil status, type of vehicle to be insured or use, among others.
Having a car is the main thing.
The fact is that choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the model of vehicle.
And it's that choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the model of the vehicle.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insurer.
This compromise is made through an insurance contract, which establishes that the company receives the value of the premium granted and in return becomes liable for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a loss.
The premium is the price of the insurance, which is determined by taking into account various factors such as age, gender, age of the driving licence, civil status, type of vehicle to be insured or use, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices based on statistics, so that the higher the likelihood of an accident, the higher the premium to pay.
This is why people over 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, as statistics show that these people have a lower accident rate than they should.
Similarly, using censuses, companies have concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will affect the frequency and therefore the likelihood of an accident.
Increasing the frequency increases the probability.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when setting the premium price.
The driver must therefore carefully consider the situation in order to choose the best car insurance for his or her profile.
We will present here the most significant variables when choosing one or the other type of insurance, so that it, in addition to adapting to the insurer's characteristics, offers a reasonable price.
Young people under 25 have to face various disadvantages when entering into a contract with an insurance at an affordable price, such as low driving experience and old driving licence.
Although the ideal insurance is a high-risk insurance, there are other, more economical options.
The most prudent drivers can opt for risk-free insurance so that they can get the coverage of risk-free insurance at a more affordable price.
This type of agreement involves the customer paying part of the amount of the loss.
"The part of the amount of the claim that the customer pays will be determined by the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount", says Luis Noguera, the manager in Spain of First Europa, online insurance intermediary.
Another option is extended third party insurance, so that the customer provides protection for damage caused to third parties, but by those caused to his own car.
It would also be protected from theft, fire, and vehicle loss.
I'll give you some advice.
