Card fraud.
Would the mortgage crisis contaminate the U.S. credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, it's normal to see the wings twirling around.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is going through a critical phase, predators are targeting the U.S. credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts believe credit card losses could reach $99 billion if the contagion spreads from mortgages to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in the rates of fees and insolvencies, which measure the non-recoverable or non-recoverable shares of the balance sheet more than 30 days later.
HSBC announced last month that it had taken $1.4 billion in its consumer loans, partly because of weak cardholders.
It's still too early to panic.
The costs and insolvencies are still moderate.
According to Moody's, a tax agency, the third quarter's 3.89% insolvency rate is almost one point lower than its historical average.
The deterioration in rates is partly explained by technical factors.
A change in the laws in 2005 in the United States regarding personal bankruptcy caused a sharp drop in bankruptcy records, which in turn caused heavy losses for credit cards; the number of records (and thus insolvency rates) could increase even if borrowing conditions worsened.
The industry also advertises fixed payment rates, which highlight the amount of monthly debt consumers have to pay.
The Commission has also taken a number of measures to ensure that the credit card sector is not affected by the financial crisis.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicted that the volume of emissions for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
The direct contagious links between the mortgage crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers may prefer to increase their debt now that fair housing loans have disappeared.
But credit card issuers pay more attention to cash flow than to the value of assets, and so the fall in real estate prices did not necessarily change the credibility of borrowers.
They could even benefit credit card issuers.
Consumer premiums for mortgage payments fall if the property costs less than the value of the loan; therefore, credit card debt would become a priority for repaying the whole.
Card issuers are able to respond much faster than mortgage lenders and with more flexibility to such crisis conditions, as they can change interest rates or alter credit limits.
This should in theory reduce the risk of a rapid recovery of stocks.
 We're not going to wake up one morning and reevaluate all loans.  said Gary Perlin, the CEO of Capital One.
If a financial disaster in the credit card market is unlikely, there is a high risk of a sharp decline.
If lower real estate prices and a contraction in the credit market are leading America into recession, the industry will certainly face a dire future.
