The British bankers have pleaded guilty to the Enron case.
The three British bankers who were due to testify about their role in a fraud committed by Enron's former chief financial officer, Andrew Fastow, changed their statement, pleading guilty Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had initially pleaded not guilty to seven counts of conspiracy to commit fraud in 2000, allegedly committed by Fastow in a secret financial scam in order to get rich despite their employees.
They should appear in court in January.
But during a hearing presided over by U.S. Justice Ewing Werlein Jr., they all pleaded guilty to fraud.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a subsidiary of the Royal Bank of Scotland PLC Group, became famous throughout Britain as a result of two-year extradition proceedings.
In the United States, their case remains a pending issue in the investigation that began after the fall of Enron in 2001.
The charges against them in 2002 made Fastow understand that he was the subject of government investigation into the Enron debacle.
The charges against the bankers, dubbed the "Natwest Three", claim they came to Houston in 2000 to set up a fraud scenario with Fastow and his former right-hander, Michael Kopper.
NatWest Greenwich invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partner controlled by Fastow, who was the setup of many fraud scenarios, which helped him rig bankruptcy proceedings.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank had estimated that its interest in the branch was zero, but in fact the three British banks already know its value.
A company controlled by Kopper bought interest in the branch bank for £1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 in interest on this company.
According to the indictment, Fastow allegedly falsely announced to Enron that the energy company was willing to pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its shares in the subsidiary.
But the truth is that these $20 million went into the pockets of British bankers, Fastow and others.
According to the charges, the bankers would have earned $7.3 while Fastow, Kopper and the others would have won $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to his active role in two conspiracies in the Enron debacle.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year sentence in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a three-year, one-month sentence in a Texas prison.
The three Britons were released following a $1 million bail each, forcing them to live in the United States during the trial.
Enron, once the seventh largest national company, went bankrupt in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks, and could no longer hide its billions in debt or even offer its junk speculation as profitable.
The collapse has resulted in thousands of layoffs, more than $60 billion in market value loss and more than $2 billion in pension loss.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their involvement in the collapse of the company.
Skilling was sentenced to more than 24 years in prison.
Charges against Lay of conspiracy, fraud and other crimes were dropped because of his death from a heart attack last year.
