Everyone hopes the Federal Reserve will lower rates linked to the global stock market boom.
Shares exploded on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday after the market hoped the Federal Reserve would try to calm credit conditions, later lowering the interest rates promoted by the soothing statements of the US central bank's vice president.
Stock markets are exploding in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, No. 2 after Ben Bernanke, Chairman of the Federal Reserve, said that decision makers must be flexible and pragmatic in their actions in the volatile financial markets.
In an apparent effort to reassure irritable markets in view of these new credit tensions, Mr Kohn said that recent turbulence had in part reversed some improvements in market performance in late September and October.
If this severe turmoil were to continue, it would increase the likelihood of further rigid financial conditions for owners and businesses, he said.
These comments appear to investors as a clear signal that the Federal Reserve is ready to inject new capital into US markets, and that further interest rate declines could stabilize credit conditions.
These remarks also calmed down Wall Street with even worse news about the U.S. economy, such as the biggest drop in real estate sales for October.
The impact of this financial turmoil was exacerbated by Bear Stearns' statement that it would lay off 650 people, or 4% of its staff, to cut costs to offset heavy losses due to losing real estate loans.
Only 20 jobs are planned in London where the bank employs 1500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 331 points, or 2.55%, to 13,289.40 while the largest index, the S&P 500, took 2.65%.
In London, the FTSE 100 index took 165.5 points or 2.7% to 6306.2 adding more than £39 to the value of UK companies.
The German Dax index rose by 2.6%, while the French CAC40 rose by 2.3%.
Previously, the re-emergence of credit difficulties in the markets was highlighted by the high demand for a monthly auction of classified funds by the European Central Bank, which cut loans to European commercial banks at a high rate of 4.7%, the highest rate since April 2001.
Pressures on the Bank of England to follow the Fed and the ECB and to inject further funds into London financial markets, causing credit tensions, have caused monthly borrowing rates by the UK banks to grow at their highest level since last September, at 6.59% following a sharp rise since 12 November.
