Venus is the infernal twin of Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus resembles Earth more than previously thought: the European space probe Venus Express has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and windstorms at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning strikes on Venus.
The European probe Venus Express has now proved this - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus is bursting at a height of about 35 miles [56 km] from the cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles in the scientific journal Nature.
According to the famous cypress theory, lightning would have produced life on Earth. The storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
"If life existed there, it must have been at a very early date in history", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be little life on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperatures sometimes reach 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the infernal twin of Earth, but she remains a twin", said Russell.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and dimensions, has been hit with such a different evolution is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The launch of the Venus Express in November 2005 was an important milestone in Venus research, as no more probes had been en route to explore the planet since the 1980s.
The researchers believe that the latest research results, now presented in several articles in Nature, not only highlight the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with our neighboring planet Earth are more numerous than originally thought.
So, in addition to the windstorms already known at the north pole, the researchers found a cloud storm at the south pole, which is turning much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents in the earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrophysics and Cosmic Physics.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet, called the evening or morning star, orbits the sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with a surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, is hardly like Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth as oceans, but lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth as carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
