These aren't Warhols' boxes.
The one who connects the Swedish concept to the wooden box is thinking about IKEA, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast a shadow over Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the 80 "Type Stockholm" Brillo-Boxs listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes a few months ago, internal research at Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now led to a disappointing result: the six Brillo-Boxes, which the former director of the museum Pontus Hulten gave to Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - as well as many of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Type Stockholm", which circulate in the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York City, painted wooden boxes, which were based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powdered soap boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet featured in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These were not (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cartonage factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not on display at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time now speak of about fifteen wooden boxes that would have gone down in history at the time as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo-Boxes, with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of these have reached auction sales of over $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum later falsely claimed that about a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and displayed in Sweden in 1968 and that Warhol would later sell them to him.
In fact, the 105 cases of Hultén were produced in Malmö only in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined three other Swedish private collections, including two made in Stockholm in 1968: their layered panels were first printed and stamped, then applied with a white oil paint brush.
The texture of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly without a layer of background to the laminated panels, using a roll of paint - and it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes", suggests Moderna Museet Director Lars Nittve: "Unless the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York makes another decision, Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material".
In July the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "heavy charges" raised in the case of the soap powder cases.
But since then, we've been in a constant silence.
